Let $s$ be the semiperimeter of $\triangle ABC,$ and let $r$ be the inradius.  Then $AD = \frac{2}{3} \cdot \frac{2}{3} s = \frac{4s}{9}.$  Also, $DG = \frac{2}{3} GD,$ so
\[\frac{4s}{9} = DG = DB - BG = \frac{1}{2} BC - BG = 10 - BG.\]Then $BG = \frac{10 - 4s/9}{1/3} = \frac{30 - 4s}{3}.$

By Heron's formula, the area of $\triangle ABC$ is
\[\sqrt{s(s - a)(s - b)(s - c)} = \sqrt{30 \cdot 10 \cdot 10 \cdot 10} = 100 \sqrt{3}.\]Also, $s = 10 + \frac{BC}{2} = 20,$ so $r = \frac{K}{s} = \frac{5 \sqrt{3}}{3}.$

By the Two Tangent Theorem, $AE = AF = s - a = 10.$  Hence, $BE = BD - DE = s - c - r = 10 - 20/3 - 5 \sqrt{3}/3 = \frac{5 - 5 \sqrt{3}}{3},$ and $CF = CD - DF = s - b - r = 10 - 20/3 - 5 \sqrt{3}/3 = \frac{5 - 5 \sqrt{3}}{3}.$

Then $BC = BE + CF + 2r = \frac{10 - 4 \sqrt{3}}{3} + \frac{10 - 4 \sqrt{3}}{3} + \frac{10 \sqrt{3}}{3} = \frac{20 - 8 \sqrt{3} + 10 \sqrt{3}}{3} = \frac{20 + 2 \sqrt{3}}{3},$ so $n = 3^2,$ and $m + n = 20 + 9 = \boxed{029}.$

