Let $s$ be the semiperimeter of $\triangle ABC,$ and let $r$ be the inradius.  Then $s = \frac{20 + AB + AC}{2}.$  By Heron's formula,
\[\sqrt{s(s - AB)(s - AC)(s - BC)} = [ABC] = rs = r \cdot 15.\]Since $s - BC = \frac{AB + AC}{2},$
\begin{align*}
\sqrt{(s - BC)(s - AB)(s - AC)BC} &= r \cdot 15 \\
\sqrt{\left( \frac{AB + AC}{2} \right) \cdot \frac{3AB + 3AC - BC}{2} \cdot \frac{3AB + 3AC + BC}{2} \cdot BC} &= r \cdot 15 \\
\sqrt{\frac{3AB + 3AC - BC}{2} \cdot \frac{3AB + 3AC + BC}{2} \cdot BC} &= r \cdot 15 \\
\sqrt{(3AB + 3AC)^2 - BC^2} &= r \cdot 15 \\
\sqrt{20^2 - BC^2} &= r \cdot 15 \\
r &= \frac{4 \sqrt{15}}{3}.
\end{align*}Then
\[\frac{AD}{AG} = \frac{r}{GM} = \frac{r}{BM - BG} = \frac{r}{10 - BG} = 3,\]so $BG = \frac{16}{3}.$  Then $CG = 20 - BG = \frac{44}{3},$ so
\[[ABC] = rs = \frac{4 \sqrt{15}}{3} \cdot 15 = 20 \sqrt{15}.\]Thus, $m + n = \boxed{35}.$

