Let $r$ be the inradius of $\triangle ABC.$  Then $BI = CI = r,$ so by Pythagoras on right triangle $BCI,$
\[BI = \sqrt{IC^2 - BC^2/4} = \sqrt{18^2 - 30^2/4} = 12\sqrt{7}.\]Also, since $AB = AC,$
\[r = AI \sin \frac{A}{2}.\]By the Law of Cosines on triangle $ABC,$
\[\cos A = \frac{AB^2 + AC^2 - BC^2}{2 AB \cdot AC} = \frac{3}{4}.\]Then $\sin A = \sqrt{1 - \cos^2 A} = \frac{\sqrt{7}}{4},$ so
\[r = AI \cdot \frac{\sqrt{7}}{4}.\]By the Law of Cosines on triangle $ABI,$
\begin{align*}
AI^2 &= AB^2 + BI^2 - 2 AB \cdot BI \cos \frac{A}{2} \\
&= AB^2 + r^2 - 2 AB \cdot r \cos \frac{A}{2} \\
&= AB^2 + r^2 - 2r(AB - 2r) \\
&= AB^2 + 4r^2 - 2r AB \\
&= AB^2 + 4r^2 - 2r (AB + AC - BC) \\
&= AB^2 + 4r^2 - 2r (2AB - BC).
\end{align*}By the Law of Cosines on triangle $ABC,$
\begin{align*}
AB^2 &= BC^2 + AC^2 - 2 BC \cdot AC \cos A \\
&= BC^2 + BC^2 - 2 BC^2 \cos A \\
&= 2 BC^2 (1 - \cos A) \\
&= 45^2 \cdot 2 \cdot \frac{3}{4} \\
&= 1012.5.
\end{align*}Hence,
\[AI^2 = 1012.5 + 4r^2 - 2r (2AB - BC).\]Also, $AI^2 = r^2 + 18^2 - 2 \cdot r \cdot 18 \cdot \cos \frac{A}{2}.$  Since $\cos \frac{A}{2} = \sqrt{\frac{1 + \cos A}{2}} = \frac{\sqrt{7}}{2},$ we can write
\[AI^2 = r^2 + 18^2 - 18r \sqrt{7}.\]Hence,
\[r^2 + 18^2 - 18r \sqrt{7} = 1012.5 + 4r^2 - 2r (2AB - BC).\]Since $AB + BC = 2AB,$ $2AB - BC = AB.$  Hence,
\[r^2 + 18^2 - 18r \sqrt{7} = 1012.5 + 4r^2 - 2r AB.\]Also, $AB^2 = 1012.5,$ so $AB = 5 \sqrt{45}.$  Substituting, we get
\[r^2 + 18^2 - 18r \sqrt{7} = 1012.5 + 4r^2 - 10r \sqrt{45}.\]Solving, we find $r = \boxed{\frac{15}{2}}.$

